t of   Lamont  .","French: habitational name from Le Mont in the Vosges or possibly other minor places so named from Old French <i>mont</i> ‘mountain’. Alternatively, a variant of   Lemond   2."]},{"name":"Lemonds","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lamont  , with English excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Lawman","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Lamont  .","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>lagman</i>, <i>lagheman</i> ‘law-man, one whose duty is to declare the law; lawyer’ (Old Norse <i>lagmann-</i>, <i>lǫgmann-</i>, oblique case of <i>lǫgmathr</i>). The word was also widely used as a personal name, Middle English <i>Lagman</i>, <i>Lagheman</i>."]},{"name":"Lamond","meanings":["Scottish, northern Irish, and French: variant of   Lamont  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Lamothe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Jacques, Pierre, Donat, Francois, Lucien, Odette, Adrien, Andree, Armand, Armande.","French: variant of   Lamotte  , or a habitational name from any of the places in France named Lamothe or La Mothe.","History: The settlement that became the city of Detroit was founded in 1701 by Antoine de la Mothe, Sieur de Cadillac (1658–1730), governor of LA. He was born into the minor nobility in Gascony, France, where his father owned the seigneury of Cadillac."]},{"name":"Lamonte","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Lamont  ."]}]},{"name":"Jennet","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a simplified spelling of   Jeannette   or a revival of a medieval pet form of the female name   Jean ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeannette","meanings":["diminutive form of <i>Jeanne</i>, feminine form of <i>Jean</i> ‘John’, now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jennet Lamont was born about 1230, in Lamont, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Malcolm MacFerchar - Lord of Co